Boil a #pot{} of salted @water{} for the noodles.

When the water is boiling, add the @egg noodles{150%grams} and cook until
softened, ~{4-6%mins}.

Drain in a #sieve{}.

Return to the pot with a splash of @oil{}. Toss to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice
into thin strips.

Zest and quarter the @lime{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1} then chop widthways into quarters.

Add the @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet} (use less if you don't like spice),
lime zest, @oil{1%tbsp}, half the garlic and half the @soy sauce{2%sachets}
to a #medium bowl{}. Stir to combine.

Pop the @prawns{180%grams} into the bowl and turn to coat well in the marinade.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Place a #pan{} over medium-high heat (without oil).

Once hot, add the prawns along with the marinade from the bowl and stir-fry
until cooked through, ~{4-6%mins}.

Once cooked, remove the pan from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: Prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Set the prawns aside and cover to keep warm.

Return the pan to high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once the pan is hot, fry the pepper and pak choi until starting to soften,
~{4-5%mins}.

Add the remaining garlic. Fry until fragrant, ~{30%secs}.

Add @water{75%ml}, the juice of 2 lime wedges, @teriyaki sauce{1%sachet} and
remaining soy sauce. Stir together and bring to the boil.

Add a splash of water to loosen the sauce if needed. Season to taste with
@salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Toss the noodles in the sauce until coated and warmed through, ~{1-2%mins}.

Roughly chop the @peanuts{20%grams}(roughly chopped).

Divide the noodles between #bowls{}.

Top with the prawns and any remaining sauce from the pan.

Finish with a scattering of peanuts.

Serve remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over.